Here is a PowerShell script to search for the industrial uses of a specified chemical. This script uses the DuckDuckGo search engine for privacy and simplicity; it does not use Internet Explorer, which is outdated and no longer supported.

To use this script:
1.  Save the code below as a `.ps1` file (e.g., `FindUses.ps1`).
2.  Open a PowerShell terminal.
3.  You may need to change the execution policy to run the script. Run this command once: `Set-ExecutionPolicy -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Scope CurrentUser`
4.  Navigate to the directory where you saved the file.
5.  Run the script by typing its name, for example: `.\FindUses.ps1`

The script will then prompt you to enter the name of the chemical you want to research.

```powershell
# This script searches for the industrial applications of a given chemical product.

function Get-ChemicalIndustrialUses {
    param (
        [Parameter(Mandatory=$true, HelpMessage="Enter the name of the chemical.")]
        [string]$ChemicalName
    )

    # Construct a search query for DuckDuckGo's HTML version.
    $encodedQuery = [System.Web.HttpUtility]::UrlEncode("$ChemicalName industrial applications")
    $searchUrl = "https://html.duckduckgo.com/html/?q=$encodedQuery"

    Write-Host "Searching for industrial uses of '$ChemicalName'..." -ForegroundColor Yellow

    try {
        # Send the web request to get the search results page.
        $response = Invoke-WebRequest -Uri $searchUrl -UseBasicParsing

        # Find all the links (<a> tags) that are search results.
        # In DuckDuckGo's HTML version, these have a class named 'result__a'.
        $resultLinks = $response.ParsedHtml.getElementsByTagName('a') | Where-Object { $_.className -eq 'result__a' }

        if ($null -ne $resultLinks) {
            Write-Host "Found $($resultLinks.Count) results:" -ForegroundColor Green
            Write-Host "-------------------------------------"

            # Loop through each result and display its title and link.
            foreach ($link in $resultLinks) {
                $title = $link.innerText.Trim()
                $url = $link.href

                Write-Host "Title: $title"
                Write-Host "Link:  $url"
                Write-Host ""
            }
        } else {
            Write-Host "No results found for '$ChemicalName'." -ForegroundColor Red
        }
    }
    catch {
        Write-Error "Failed to retrieve search results. Error: $_"
    }
}

# --- Main script execution ---
# Clear the screen for better readability.
Clear-Host

# Prompt the user to enter a chemical name.
$chemical = Read-Host "Please enter the name of the chemical to search for"

# Call the function with the user's input.
if (-not [string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($chemical)) {
    Get-ChemicalIndustrialUses -ChemicalName $chemical
} else {
    Write-Host "No chemical name entered. Exiting script." -ForegroundColor Red
}
```
